#speculation(title: [Alpha-Lipoic Acid for AQP4 Oxidation Protection])[
*Certainty: 0.35.* AQP4 is susceptible to oxidative damage, which contributes to depolarization at astrocytic endfeet. Systemic oxidative stress is documented in ME/CFS (reduced cortical glutathione, Section @sec:ch15-oxidative-stress). Alpha-lipoic acid is a potent antioxidant that crosses the BBB. By reducing AQP4 oxidation, ALA may preserve AQP4 polarization and slow diffusive glymphatic transport. Chayama et al.\ @Chayama2026BrainClearance confirm AQP4-rich perivascular spaces are the clearance conduits.

- *Falsifiable:* ME/CFS patients on ALA (600 mg daily) for 8 weeks will show preserved AQP4-mediated transport (estimated from MR-AIV permeability) compared to decline in placebo, with corresponding DTI-ALPS stabilization.
- *Limitations:* AQP4 oxidation in ME/CFS is not directly measured. DTI-ALPS is an indirect proxy.
] <spec:ala-aqp4-protection>
